1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,560
 and welcome to another walkthrough for computer architecture for everybody.

2
00:00:04,560 --> 00:00:10,200
 In this walkthrough we're going to cover the gates, the gate layout system and the gate simulation system.

3
00:00:10,200 --> 00:00:17,200
 It has an extensive help, probably more than you need if you get stuck or you want to paste some of this stuff into AI and figure out how to use it.

4
00:00:17,200 --> 00:00:19,360
 So I'm just going to walk through the basic features.

5
00:00:19,360 --> 00:00:28,360
 So we have a wide range of components, all the way from something as simple as a single AND gate, or an input or an output that we can put in,

6
00:00:28,360 --> 00:00:31,360
 or we can put something much more simpler like a Nixie display, right?

7
00:00:31,360 --> 00:00:37,360
 So if we take this Nixie display and you can drag things around and you can connect them to the input.

8
00:00:37,360 --> 00:00:40,360
 And so this is the Nixie display that's got a one, two and four input.

9
00:00:40,360 --> 00:00:45,360
 So let's play with that a little bit, give ourselves another input, click to connect them.

10
00:00:45,360 --> 00:00:50,360
 And then so I've got this Nixie input, it's a three because it's a one and a one.

11
00:00:50,360 --> 00:00:53,360
 So it's the two input is one and the one input is one.

12
00:00:53,360 --> 00:00:56,360
 Let's go ahead and bring another input in and connect it.

13
00:00:56,360 --> 00:00:58,360
 Oops, connect, connect.

14
00:00:58,360 --> 00:00:59,360
 There we go.

15
00:00:59,360 --> 00:01:03,360
 So now it is a seven, right?

16
00:01:03,360 --> 00:01:04,360
 You can do some practice.

17
00:01:04,360 --> 00:01:11,360
 So that's a four and a two and a zero, which is a six.

18
00:01:11,360 --> 00:01:13,360
 And you can rename these things.

19
00:01:13,360 --> 00:01:20,360
 So I'm going to call this one ones and call this one twos.

20
00:01:20,360 --> 00:01:26,360
 So this little tag, you can tag and then click on something and then fours.

21
00:01:26,360 --> 00:01:30,360
 So we can have the bits for the ones, twos and fours.

22
00:01:30,360 --> 00:01:32,360
 And if we turn it off, then that's going to be a two.

23
00:01:32,360 --> 00:01:33,360
 So that's a two.

24
00:01:33,360 --> 00:01:35,360
 If I add one to that, then that's three.

25
00:01:35,360 --> 00:01:37,360
 And you can just build these little circuits.

26
00:01:37,360 --> 00:01:42,360
 So one of the things that I'll just show you that is really weird is there's an automatic layout.

27
00:01:42,360 --> 00:01:48,360
 So like if I had to put this input over here, it's trying its hardest.

28
00:01:48,360 --> 00:01:52,360
 This laying out circuits is a hard thing and I've got it using spline curves.

29
00:01:52,360 --> 00:01:57,360
 But if you come over and you highlight and double click, you will create what's called a waypoint.

30
00:01:57,360 --> 00:02:03,360
 And then I can sort of route these wires creatively and then drag these waypoints.

31
00:02:03,360 --> 00:02:04,360
 It doesn't change the circuits at all.

32
00:02:04,360 --> 00:02:09,360
 And so I can make this look a little bit better using waypoints.

33
00:02:09,360 --> 00:02:12,360
 And so a couple other things, let's see.

34
00:02:12,360 --> 00:02:16,360
 We can get a component, a full ladder component.

35
00:02:16,360 --> 00:02:21,360
 So it's a carry-in, an A and a B, and then a sum and a carry-out.

36
00:02:21,360 --> 00:02:25,360
 And that is, you know, inside of that, inside of every one of these are transistors.

37
00:02:25,360 --> 00:02:27,360
 A Nixie tube has got some glowing stuff.

38
00:02:27,360 --> 00:02:30,360
 It's actually a tube. I just put it in because it's pretty.

39
00:02:30,360 --> 00:02:32,360
 We got a JK flip-flop.

40
00:02:32,360 --> 00:02:36,360
 And so a JK flip-flop, I'll go through this in a little bit more.

41
00:02:36,360 --> 00:02:40,360
 We've got even a thing called a three-bit latch, which we'll use later as a register.

42
00:02:40,360 --> 00:02:43,360
 It has some inputs and outputs and it has an internal state.

43
00:02:43,360 --> 00:02:47,360
 And the pulsing on the clock copies the input into the internal state.

44
00:02:47,360 --> 00:02:51,360
 Then letting go of the clock will copy the internal state to the output.

45
00:02:51,360 --> 00:02:58,360
 And we have a three-bit adder that takes A and B in the ones, twos, and fours column.

46
00:02:58,360 --> 00:02:59,360
 And then the sum comes out.

47
00:02:59,360 --> 00:03:04,360
 And so that is basically the kinds of things that you can do.

48
00:03:04,360 --> 00:03:09,360
 And remember that every one of these things eventually turns into transistors.

49
00:03:09,360 --> 00:03:17,360
 So I showed you the tag. The tag, you just grab something and then fun and you just give it a name.

50
00:03:17,360 --> 00:03:19,360
 And so that gives these things names.

51
00:03:19,360 --> 00:03:24,360
 You can delete something by clicking the trash can icon and then highlighting an item and it deletes it.

52
00:03:24,360 --> 00:03:30,360
 And if you click and delete something that has a wire associated with it, it deletes the wire as well.

53
00:03:30,360 --> 00:03:37,360
 You can save a circuit, stuff, and it saves the circuit inside your browser

54
00:03:37,360 --> 00:03:39,360
 and what's called local storage in your browser.

55
00:03:39,360 --> 00:03:40,360
 And then you can load it.

56
00:03:40,360 --> 00:03:44,360
 So if you're in the middle of working on something and you want to save it and load it,

57
00:03:44,360 --> 00:03:45,360
 well, let me do this.

58
00:03:45,360 --> 00:03:49,360
 I'm going to clear all of them, clear everything, get rid of everything.

59
00:03:49,360 --> 00:03:53,360
 And now I can reload that circuit from the storage that was called stuff.

60
00:03:53,360 --> 00:03:55,360
 It was a crazy circuit.

61
00:03:55,360 --> 00:03:57,360
 So I just loaded stuff back up.

62
00:03:57,360 --> 00:03:58,360
 And so that was that circuit.

63
00:03:58,360 --> 00:03:59,360
 I saved it. I loaded it.

64
00:03:59,360 --> 00:04:01,360
 You could load it. You could add a thing.

65
00:04:01,360 --> 00:04:05,360
 Let's add another input and then connect it up.

66
00:04:05,360 --> 00:04:10,360
 And then save it as stuff again.

67
00:04:10,360 --> 00:04:11,360
 Save.

68
00:04:11,360 --> 00:04:17,360
 OK, now let's clear everything again.

69
00:04:17,360 --> 00:04:20,360
 And then load stuff back up.

70
00:04:20,360 --> 00:04:25,360
 And you should see.

71
00:04:25,360 --> 00:04:26,360
 And it's edited.

72
00:04:26,360 --> 00:04:27,360
 See, I can load it.

73
00:04:27,360 --> 00:04:31,360
 I can edit it and then save it and then load it again.

74
00:04:31,360 --> 00:04:34,360
 If you are to go and relaunch this, I'll just refresh the page

75
00:04:34,360 --> 00:04:36,360
 and you'll see what happens here.

76
00:04:36,360 --> 00:04:37,360
 It's gone.

77
00:04:37,360 --> 00:04:39,360
 That's all just in the browser storage.

78
00:04:39,360 --> 00:04:44,360
 But if you were clever enough to save it, you can load it back up.

79
00:04:44,360 --> 00:04:48,360
 So again, depending on how complex the work that you're going to do,

80
00:04:48,360 --> 00:04:50,360
 you can use load and save.

81
00:04:50,360 --> 00:04:52,360
 So let's go through a couple of other things.

82
00:04:52,360 --> 00:04:55,360
 Like I mentioned, if you're trying to make the wires route nicely,

83
00:04:55,360 --> 00:04:57,360
 you can double click on the line and create a waypoint.

84
00:04:57,360 --> 00:05:00,360
 And I don't know why, but I have a thing to hide the waypoints

85
00:05:00,360 --> 00:05:02,360
 if you don't want to see them and then show them back.

86
00:05:02,360 --> 00:05:07,360
 There's also a command down here, and that's described in the help documentation.

87
00:05:07,360 --> 00:05:09,360
 So you can say place NAND.

88
00:05:09,360 --> 00:05:12,360
 And so it'll put a NAND in there.

89
00:05:12,360 --> 00:05:14,360
 If you really want to read the instructions,

90
00:05:14,360 --> 00:05:18,360
 and I did this to some degree for accessibility,

91
00:05:18,360 --> 00:05:21,360
 where you can place a NAND and give it a name,

92
00:05:21,360 --> 00:05:24,360
 and then you can connect the output of the NAND to the input of something.

93
00:05:24,360 --> 00:05:26,360
 We'll see how well people find that to use.

94
00:05:26,360 --> 00:05:27,360
 I put it in there.

95
00:05:27,360 --> 00:05:29,360
 I may have to work on it and improve it over time.

96
00:05:29,360 --> 00:05:31,360
 You can show how to hide the command line interface.

97
00:05:31,360 --> 00:05:37,360
 I hope that this basic walkthrough of the Gates layout tool has been helpful to you.

